cs.CG, cs.DS, cs.DM, cs.CC, cs.NA. 

The paper deals with geometric objects and their properties, which suggests that it belongs to the computational geometry (cs.CG) sub-category. The use of sets and families of objects also suggests that it could belong to the data structures (cs.DS) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM) sub-categories. The study of unbiased representatives and balancing of colors suggests that it could belong to the computational complexity (cs.CC) sub-category. Finally, the use of Euclidean balls and the study of random distributions suggests that it could belong to the numerical analysis (cs.NA) sub-category.
